<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What DPI do I need for high-quality prints?", answer: "For high-quality photo prints, 300 DPI is the industry standard. At 300 DPI, individual pixels are invisible to the naked eye at normal viewing distance. For large prints viewed from farther away (posters, banners), 150-200 DPI is often sufficient. Fine art and gallery prints may use 360 DPI or higher." },
  { question: "How do I calculate print size from pixels?", answer: "Divide the pixel dimension by the DPI to get the print size in inches. For example, a 6000x4000 pixel image at 300 DPI prints at 20x13.3 inches. To convert to centimeters, multiply inches by 2.54." },
  { question: "What resolution do I need for a 24x36 poster?", answer: "For a 24x36 inch poster at 300 DPI, you need 7200x10800 pixels (77.8 megapixels). However, since posters are typically viewed from a distance, 150 DPI is usually sufficient, requiring only 3600x5400 pixels (19.4 megapixels)." },
  { question: "What is the difference between DPI and PPI?", answer: "PPI (pixels per inch) describes the resolution of a digital image or screen, while DPI (dots per inch) describes the output resolution of a printer. In practice, the terms are often used interchangeably when discussing print resolution." },
  { question: "How many megapixels do I need for large prints?", answer: "For an 8x10 print at 300 DPI, you need 7.2 megapixels. For a 16x20 print, you need 28.8 megapixels. For a 24x36 print at 300 DPI, you need 77.8 megapixels, though 150 DPI (19.4 MP) is acceptable for wall-sized prints." }
]) %>

